05341nam a22008895i 9783110689273DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020946506  a97831106892737 a10.1515/97831106892732doi  a(DE-B1597)541930  a(OCoLC)1233041550  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPR4611.A73bA76 2021 7aLIT0041202bisacsh0484pa800qDE-1011 aArnavas, Francesca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLewis Carroll's "Alice" and Cognitive Narratology :bAuthor, Reader and Characters /cFrancesca Arnavas. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (XXI, 203 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarratologia ;v73  aDissertationcYorkd2018.00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Abbreviations -- tQuotations in Headings -- tPreface. Pictures and Conversations -- tChapter 1. Why the Alices? -- tChapter 2. Virtual Alice -- tChapter 3. Mirrored Alice -- tChapter 4. Emotional Alice -- tChapter 5. Unnatural Alice -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tAuthors Index -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe live in an age that is witnessing a growing interest in narrative studies, cognitive neuroscientific tools, mind studies and artificial intelligence hypotheses. This book therefore aims to expand the exegesis of Carroll's "Alice" books, aligning them with the current intellectual environment. The theoretical force of this volume lies in the successful encounter between a great book (and all its polysemous ramifications) and a new interpretative point of view, powerful enough to provide a new original contribution, but well grounded enough not to distort the text itself. Moreover, this book is one of the first to offer a complete, thorough analysis of one single text through the theoretical lens of cognitive narratology, and not just as a series of brief examples embedded within a more general discussion. It emphasises in a more direct, effective way the actual novelty and usefulness of the dialogue established between narrative theory and the cognitive sciences. It links specific concepts elaborated in the theory of cognitive narratology with the analysis of the "Alice" books, helping in this way to discuss, question and extend the concepts themselves, opening up new interpretations and practical methods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aChildrenxBooks and readingzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aChildren's stories, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aFantasy fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAlice Books.  aCognitive Narratology.  aLewis Carroll.  aUnnatural Narratology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831106893030 cprintz978311068907540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311068927340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110689273423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110689273/original  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Pl